ðŸš€ 1. Setup & Import
code
Python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Optional: Set a professional style (like 'ggplot', 'seaborn', or 'fivethirtyeight')
plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-darkgrid')
ðŸ“ˆ 2. Essential Plot Types
Plot Type	Command	Best Used For...
Line Plot	plt.plot(x, y)	Trends over time/continuous data
Scatter Plot	plt.scatter(x, y)	Relationship/correlation between variables
Bar Chart	plt.bar(x, height)	Comparing categories
Histogram	plt.hist(data, bins=10)	Distribution of numerical data
Pie Chart	plt.pie(sizes, labels=labels)	Parts of a whole (use sparingly!)[2][3][4][5]
Box Plot	plt.boxplot(data)	Statistical outliers and quartiles
ðŸŽ¨ 3. Customization (Labels & Titles)
code
Python
plt.plot(x, y)
plt.title("Growth of Data Science ðŸš€", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Demand (%)")
plt.legend(["Trendline"], loc="upper left")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
plt.show()
ðŸŒˆ 4. Styling (Colors, Lines, & Markers)
Parameter	Values	Example
Color	'red', 'g', '#4C72B0'	color='purple'
Line Style	'-', '--', '-.', ':'	linestyle='--'
Marker	'o', 's', '^', '*'	marker='o'
Linewidth	Numeric value	linewidth=2.5
Transparency	0 to 1	alpha=0.5
ðŸªŸ 5. Subplots (Multiple Charts)
code
Python
# Create a grid of 1 row and 2 columns
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 4))

ax1.plot(x, y, color='blue')
ax1.set_title("Line Chart")

ax2.scatter(x, y, color='orange')
ax2.set_title("Scatter Plot")

plt.tight_layout() # Prevents overlapping
plt.show()
ðŸ’¾ 6. Figure Management
Command	Description
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))	Set the size of your canvas (inches)
plt.savefig("my_plot.png", dpi=300)	Save your chart in high quality
plt.clf()	Clear the current figure
plt.close()	Close the window (saves memory)
ðŸ’¡ Pro-Tips for the Lab:
Object-Oriented Approach: Using fig, ax = plt.subplots() is the industry standard for complex projects.
Save Before Show: Always run plt.savefig() before plt.show(), or your saved file might be blank!
Readability: Always add labels (xlabel, ylabel)â€”a graph without labels is just a drawing, not a data insight. âœ¨
